## Change Classification and AO Notification Threshold

Not every change requires AO notification — notifying the AO of every routine patch cycle would dilute the significance of genuine notifications and burden the AO unnecessarily. The classification framework:

| Change Type | SSP Update? | AO Notification? | Timeline |
|---|---|---|---|
| Routine security patch (OS, libraries) | No — change log only | No | Within 14 days of patch |
| OpenMRS version update | Yes — update component versions | No (unless introduces new controls) | Before production deployment |
| New OpenMRS module | Yes — SIA required; SSP updated | Only if creates new risk above baseline | Before production deployment |
| New IAM entity | Yes — IAM inventory update | No (EventBridge auto-notification to ISSO) | Before granting access |
| Security group change | Yes if access scope changes | If opens new inbound access | Within 24 hours |
| New system interconnection | Yes — interconnection section update | Yes — new BAA/ISA required | Before integration |
| New data type processed | Yes — possible categorization review | Yes — potential re-authorization | Before new data flows |
| Threat landscape: new relevant CVE | POA&M if not patched within SLA | If High severity unpatched | Per severity SLA |
| Regulatory change (new HIPAA guidance) | If affects control implementation | If affects authorization basis | Within 90 days of guidance |
| Significant staff change (ISSO departure) | Succession documentation | Yes — AO must designate new ISSO | Immediately |

The last entry — ISSO departure — is the single environmental change that requires the most careful handling. If the ISSO who built this security program departs, the AO needs to know immediately, because the authorization assumptions include the existence of a qualified, knowledgeable ISSO executing the continuous monitoring program. The archival README document from Day 68 is what makes the succession less catastrophic — but it does not eliminate the need for AO notification and an expedited onboarding process for the successor.

