## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While developing the module addition SIA example today — specifically the dependency scanning step — I thought about the **2021 Log4Shell vulnerability (CVE-2021-44228)** and how it affected OpenMRS directly.

Log4Shell was a critical Remote Code Execution vulnerability in the Log4j Java logging library, disclosed in December 2021. OpenMRS uses Java, and some versions of OpenMRS and its modules included Log4j as a dependency. The OpenMRS community issued security advisories and patches, but organizations running OpenMRS needed to identify whether their specific deployment used an affected version of Log4j and in what context.

The organizations that responded fastest to Log4Shell were the ones that had dependency inventories — systems that knew which libraries were present in their deployments. The SIA process for module additions builds exactly that kind of institutional knowledge incrementally: every module installation is accompanied by a dependency scan, so the ISSO always has a reasonably current picture of what libraries are present in the OpenMRS deployment.

An organization that installed modules without SIA over several years arrived at Log4Shell with no idea whether they were affected. An organization that practiced M-1 change monitoring consistently arrived at Log4Shell with an Inspector scan history and a dependency list that made the impact assessment take hours instead of weeks.

This is the compounding value of disciplined M-1 monitoring — it is not just about the changes being monitored; it is about building the organizational knowledge base that makes future rapid response possible.

