## What I Am Still Thinking About

The environmental monitoring program I described today relies heavily on ISSO initiative — weekly threat briefing reviews, monthly CISA catalog scans, quarterly SSP accuracy reviews. These are calendar-driven activities that the ISSO needs to execute consistently to be meaningful.

The AT-2 quarterly training review lapse in Day 55 — where a calendar-driven activity fell through the cracks — is a reminder that ISSO capacity is finite and competing priorities exist. The M-1 environmental monitoring activities are less automated than the technical monitoring (GuardDuty, Config, Inspector run automatically) and more dependent on disciplined ISSO execution.

One way to strengthen the environmental monitoring is to build accountability into it beyond the ISSO's personal calendar. Monthly ISSO threat briefing notes, shared with the Health IT Manager, serve two purposes: they document that the monitoring occurred (accountability), and they keep the Health IT Manager informed about the threat landscape affecting their clinical system (organizational awareness). If the ISSO misses a monthly briefing, the Health IT Manager notices the absence of the monthly note — creating a lightweight peer accountability mechanism.

This kind of distributed accountability — not surveillance, but shared visibility — is what makes security programs resilient to the capacity constraints that affect every small organization's security function.

